DLL Hijacking Investigation

"To keep you sharp, your SOC manager has assigned you the task of analyzing older attack logs and providing answers to specific questions."

Scenario

The objective of this investigation was to identify the executable responsible for performing a DLL hijacking attack by analyzing Sysmon logs located in:

C:\Logs\DLLHijack
Understanding the Attack

DLL Hijacking occurs when a legitimate executable loads a malicious DLL placed in a location controlled by an attacker.

A common technique involves:

Copying a legitimate executable to another directory
Placing a malicious DLL with the expected name alongside it
Forcing the executable to load the malicious DLL instead of the legitimate system DLL
Investigation Strategy

I focused on:

Sysmon Event ID 7 — Image Loaded

This event provides:

Field	Description
Image	Executable that loaded the DLL
ImageLoaded	DLL that was loaded
Signed	Whether the DLL is digitally signed
Signature	Digital signature information

Because the logs contained many legitimate DLL loads, I reduced noise by excluding common trusted Windows paths such as:

C:\Windows\
C:\Program Files\

I then focused on suspicious indicators including:

DLLs loaded from:
ProgramData
Temp
Desktop
Downloads
Users
Unsigned DLLs
Legitimate executables executing outside System32
PowerShell Investigation Command
Get-ChildItem "C:\Logs\DLLHijack" -Filter *.evtx |
ForEach-Object {
    Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{Path=$_.FullName; Id=7} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
} |
ForEach-Object {
    $xml = [xml]$_.ToXml()
    $d = $xml.Event.EventData.Data

    [PSCustomObject]@{
        Time        = $_.TimeCreated
        Image       = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "Image"}).'#text'
        ImageLoaded = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "ImageLoaded"}).'#text'
        Signed      = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "Signed"}).'#text'
        Signature   = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "Signature"}).'#text'
    }
} |
Where-Object {
    $_.ImageLoaded -like "*.dll" -and
    $_.ImageLoaded -notlike "C:\Windows\*" -and
    $_.ImageLoaded -notlike "C:\Program Files*" -and
    (
        $_.Signed -eq "false" -or
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "C:\Users\*" -or
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "*\Temp\*" -or
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "*\Desktop\*" -or
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "*\Downloads\*" -or
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "*\ProgramData\*"
    )
} |
Sort-Object Time |
Format-List
Suspicious Events Identified
Time        : 4/27/2022 6:39:11 PM
Image       : C:\ProgramData\Dism.exe
ImageLoaded : C:\ProgramData\DismCore.dll
Signed      : false
Signature   : -

Additional related event:

Time        : 4/27/2022 6:39:30 PM
Image       : C:\Windows\System32\rundll32.exe
ImageLoaded : C:\ProgramData\DismCore.dll
Signed      : false
Signature   : -
Conclusion

The executable responsible for the DLL hijacking attack was:

Dism.exe

This conclusion was reached because:

Dism.exe normally resides in:
C:\Windows\System32\
However, a copy was found executing from:
C:\ProgramData\
The executable loaded:
DismCore.dll

also located in ProgramData and lacking a valid digital signature.

This behavior strongly indicates DLL hijacking, where an attacker copied a legitimate executable into a writable directory and placed a malicious DLL alongside it in order to force the executable to load attacker-controlled code.

Unmanaged PowerShell Execution Investigation
Scenario

The objective of this investigation was to identify the process responsible for executing unmanaged PowerShell code by analyzing logs located in:

C:\Logs\PowershellExec
Understanding the Attack

Unmanaged PowerShell refers to PowerShell execution occurring inside another process without directly launching:

powershell.exe

Instead, attackers inject the .NET runtime and PowerShell components into another legitimate process to evade detection.

Normally, PowerShell activity would involve:

powershell.exe

loading .NET-related DLLs such as:

clr.dll
clrjit.dll
mscoree.dll
Investigation Strategy

I focused on:

Sysmon Event ID 7 — Image Loaded

The goal was to identify processes that:

Were NOT:
powershell.exe
pwsh.exe
powershell_ise.exe
BUT still loaded .NET runtime DLLs

Indicators used:

mscoree.dll
clr.dll
clrjit.dll
System.Management.Automation.dll
PowerShell Investigation Command
Get-ChildItem "C:\Logs\PowershellExec" -Filter *.evtx |
ForEach-Object {
    Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{Path=$_.FullName; Id=7} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
} |
ForEach-Object {
    $xml = [xml]$_.ToXml()
    $d = $xml.Event.EventData.Data

    [PSCustomObject]@{
        Time        = $_.TimeCreated
        Image       = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "Image"}).'#text'
        ImageLoaded = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "ImageLoaded"}).'#text'
        Signed      = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "Signed"}).'#text'
        Signature   = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "Signature"}).'#text'
    }
} |
Where-Object {
    (
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "*clr.dll" -or
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "*clrjit.dll" -or
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "*mscoree.dll" -or
        $_.ImageLoaded -like "*System.Management.Automation.dll"
    ) -and
    $_.Image -notlike "*powershell.exe" -and
    $_.Image -notlike "*pwsh.exe" -and
    $_.Image -notlike "*powershell_ise.exe"
} |
Sort-Object Time |
