Process Injection Investigation
Scenario

After identifying that Calculator.exe executed unmanaged PowerShell code, the next objective was to determine which process injected into it.

Understanding the Attack

Attackers frequently use:

Process Injection
Remote Thread Creation
DLL Injection

to execute malicious code inside legitimate processes.

The most relevant event for this behavior is:

Sysmon Event ID 8 — CreateRemoteThread

This event records when one process creates a thread inside another process.

Investigation Strategy

I searched for:

TargetImage = Calculator.exe

while analyzing Event ID 8 entries.

PowerShell Investigation Command
Get-ChildItem "C:\Logs\PowershellExec" -Filter *.evtx |
ForEach-Object {
    Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{Path=$_.FullName; Id=8} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
} |
ForEach-Object {
    $xml = [xml]$_.ToXml()
    $d = $xml.Event.EventData.Data

    [PSCustomObject]@{
        Time          = $_.TimeCreated
        SourceImage   = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "SourceImage"}).'#text'
        TargetImage   = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "TargetImage"}).'#text'
        StartModule   = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "StartModule"}).'#text'
        StartFunction = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "StartFunction"}).'#text'
    }
} |
Where-Object {
    $_.TargetImage -like "*Calculator.exe"
} |
Format-List
Suspicious Events Identified
Time          : 4/27/2022 6:59:42 PM
SourceImage   : C:\Windows\System32\rundll32.exe
TargetImage   : C:\Program Files\WindowsApps\Microsoft.WindowsCalculator_10.1906.55.0_x64__8wekyb3d8bbwe\Calculator.exe
StartModule   : -
StartFunction : -

Additional event:

Time          : 4/27/2022 7:00:13 PM
SourceImage   : C:\Windows\System32\rundll32.exe
TargetImage   : C:\Program Files\WindowsApps\Microsoft.WindowsCalculator_10.1906.55.0_x64__8wekyb3d8bbwe\Calculator.exe
StartModule   : -
StartFunction : -
Conclusion

The process responsible for injecting into Calculator.exe was:

rundll32.exe

This conclusion was based on the SourceImage field from:

Sysmon Event ID 8 — CreateRemoteThread

Relationship identified:

rundll32.exe → Calculator.exe
LSASS Dump Investigation
Scenario

The objective of this investigation was to identify the process responsible for performing suspicious access against:

lsass.exe

which is commonly associated with credential dumping activity.

Understanding the Attack

lsass.exe (Local Security Authority Subsystem Service) stores authentication-related data and credentials in memory, making it a common target for tools such as:

Mimikatz
Process Hacker
Dumpert
comsvcs.dll dumping
Investigation Strategy

I focused on:

Sysmon Event ID 10 — Process Access

This event records when one process attempts to access another process.

Relevant fields:

Field	Description
SourceImage	Process initiating access
TargetImage	Target process
GrantedAccess	Access level requested

The investigation focused on:

TargetImage = lsass.exe

Noise reduction included excluding common legitimate system processes such as:

svchost.exe
MsMpEng.exe
csrss.exe
wininit.exe

The objective was to identify:

Unusual processes
Suspicious execution paths
High access permissions
PowerShell Investigation Command
Get-ChildItem "C:\Logs\Dump" -Filter *.evtx |
ForEach-Object {
    Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{Path=$_.FullName; Id=10} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
} |
ForEach-Object {

    $xml = [xml]$_.ToXml()
    $d = $xml.Event.EventData.Data

    [PSCustomObject]@{
        Time          = $_.TimeCreated
        SourceImage   = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "SourceImage"}).'#text'
        TargetImage   = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "TargetImage"}).'#text'
        GrantedAccess = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "GrantedAccess"}).'#text'
    }
} |
Where-Object {
    $_.TargetImage -like "*lsass.exe"
} |
Format-List
Suspicious Event Identified
Time          : 4/27/2022 7:08:56 PM
SourceImage   : C:\Users\waldo\Downloads\processhacker-3.0.4801-bin\64bit\ProcessHacker.exe
TargetImage   : C:\Windows\system32\lsass.exe
GrantedAccess : 0x1fffff
Analysis

The strongest indicator was:

GrantedAccess : 0x1fffff

This value corresponds to extremely high privileges, effectively equivalent to:

PROCESS_ALL_ACCESS

Credential dumping tools require this level of access to:

Read LSASS memory
Extract NTLM hashes
Dump plaintext credentials
Enumerate security tokens

Additionally, the executable was launched from:

C:\Users\waldo\Downloads\

which further increased suspicion because legitimate administrative tools typically do not operate against LSASS from a Downloads directory.

Conclusion

The process responsible for the LSASS dump activity was:

ProcessHacker.exe
Post-Dump Login Investigation
Scenario

After identifying LSASS dumping activity, the next objective was to determine whether the stolen credentials were later used for malicious authentication activity.

Investigation Logic

The reasoning followed this chain:

LSASS Dump
→ Credential Theft
→ Potential Credential Reuse

The dump activity occurred around:

7:08 PM

Therefore, I analyzed authentication events occurring after that timestamp.

Relevant Security Events
Event ID	Description
4624	Successful Logon
4625	Failed Logon
4672	Special Privileges Assigned

The primary focus was:

Event ID 4624 — Successful Logon
PowerShell Investigation Command
Get-ChildItem "C:\Logs\Dump" -Filter *.evtx |
ForEach-Object {
    Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{Path=$_.FullName; Id=4624} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
} |
Where-Object {
    $_.TimeCreated -gt (Get-Date "04/27/2022 7:08:00 PM")
} |
ForEach-Object {

    $xml = [xml]$_.ToXml()
    $d = $xml.Event.EventData.Data

    [PSCustomObject]@{
        Time        = $_.TimeCreated
        User        = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "TargetUserName"}).'#text'
        LogonType   = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "LogonType"}).'#text'
        Workstation = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "WorkstationName"}).'#text'
        SourceIP    = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "IpAddress"}).'#text'
    }
} |
Format-Table -AutoSize
Results

The observed authentication events after the dump activity showed:

Logon Type = 5
Analysis

Logon Type 5 corresponds to:

Service Logon

This authentication type is commonly associated with:

Windows Services
Scheduled Tasks
Service Accounts

No indicators suggesting malicious credential reuse were observed.

Conclusion

Was there evidence of an ill-intended login after the LSASS dump?

No
Strange Parent-Child Relationship Investigation
Scenario

The objective of this investigation was to identify a process used for temporary code execution based on an abnormal parent-child process relationship.

This type of behavior is commonly associated with:

PPID Spoofing
Process Masquerading
Temporary Command Execution
Investigation Strategy

I focused on:

Sysmon Event ID 1 — Process Create

This event provides:

Executed process
Parent process
Command line arguments

To reduce noise, I excluded common legitimate parent processes such as:

explorer.exe
cmd.exe
powershell.exe
services.exe
svchost.exe

I then searched for temporary command execution patterns involving:

cmd.exe
whoami.exe
powershell.exe

spawned by unusual parent processes.

PowerShell Investigation Command
Get-ChildItem "C:\Logs\StrangePPID" -Filter *.evtx |
ForEach-Object {
    Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{Path=$_.FullName; Id=1} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
} |
ForEach-Object {

    $xml = [xml]$_.ToXml()
    $d = $xml.Event.EventData.Data

    [PSCustomObject]@{
        Time              = $_.TimeCreated
        Image             = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "Image"}).'#text'
        ParentImage       = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "ParentImage"}).'#text'
        CommandLine       = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "CommandLine"}).'#text'
        ParentCommandLine = ($d | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "ParentCommandLine"}).'#text'
    }
} |
Where-Object {

    $_.ParentImage -notlike "*explorer.exe" -and
    $_.ParentImage -notlike "*cmd.exe" -and
    $_.ParentImage -notlike "*powershell.exe" -and
    $_.ParentImage -notlike "*services.exe" -and
    $_.ParentImage -notlike "*svchost.exe"

} |
Format-List
Suspicious Event Identified
Time              : 4/27/2022 7:18:06 PM
Image             : C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe
ParentImage       : C:\Windows\System32\werfault.exe
CommandLine       : cmd.exe /c whoami
ParentCommandLine : "C:\Windows\System32\werfault.exe"
Analysis

The activity was considered suspicious because:

werfault.exe

is normally associated with:

Windows Error Reporting

and does not typically spawn:

cmd.exe

as a child process.

Additionally, the executed command:

cmd.exe /c whoami

is extremely common in:

Quick execution tests
Privilege validation
Post-exploitation activity
PPID spoofing scenarios
Conclusion

The process used for temporary code execution was:

cmd.exe
